    "body": "### Problem\n\n- Severity: `Medium`\n- Affected locations:\n  - `runtime/autoload/provider/node.vim:46`\n  - `runtime/autoload/provider/node.vim:59`\n  - `runtime/autoload/provider/node.vim:76`\n  - `runtime/autoload/provider/node.vim:83`\n- Trigger points:\n  - `provider#node#Detect()`\n  - `jobstart('npm --loglevel silent root -g', ...)`\n  - `jobstart('yarn global dir', ...)`\n  - `jobstart('pnpm --loglevel silent root -g', ...)`\n\nWhen detecting the Node host, `provider#node#Detect()` only uses `executable('npm')`, `executable('yarn')`, and `executable('pnpm')` to determine command availability, then directly executes the corresponding command.\n\nThis logic does not first call `dist#vim#IsSafeExecutable()` to reject executable files with the same name from the current directory, unlike `runtime/autoload/gzip.vim` and `runtime/ftplugin/perl.vim`. Therefore, when the user's `PATH` contains `.` or a priority directory can be controlled by an attacker, Neovim may execute a malicious `npm`/`yarn`/`pnpm` during the provider detection phase.\n\nThis issue has been verified to exist, but the prerequisite is that the local `PATH` is insecure or that a priority directory can be controlled by an attacker. This is not a remotely exploitable vulnerability by default, nor is it an issue that necessarily triggers on normal Neovim startup.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create a temporary directory, e.g., `/tmp/cwdhijack-node`.\n2. Write a malicious `npm` script in that directory and make it executable.\n3. Prepend the current directory to `PATH`, e.g., `PATH=.:$PATH`.\n4. Start Neovim in that directory and call `provider#node#Detect()`.\n5. Check whether `/tmp/cwdhijack-node-fired` has been created.\n\n```sh\nmkdir -p /tmp/cwdhijack-node\ncat >/tmp/cwdhijack-node/npm <<'EOF'\n#!/bin/sh\necho Pwned >/tmp/cwdhijack-node-fired\nprintf '/nonexistent\\n'\nexit 0\nEOF\nchmod +x /tmp/cwdhijack-node/npm\n\ncd /tmp/cwdhijack-node\nPATH=.:$PATH nvim --headless -u NONE \"+call provider#node#Detect()\" +qall\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n### Impact\n\n- Executes an attacker-controlled local program with the current user's privileges.\n- No need for the user to explicitly run commands like `:!npm`; triggering node provider detection is sufficient.\n- Trigger points typically include explicitly calling `provider#node#Detect()`, or executing functional paths that require loading the node provider.\n- Suitable for bait repositories, malicious working directories, or contaminated development environments for local code execution or privilege escalation as a precursor.\n- A normal `nvim --headless -u NONE -i NONE +qall` startup does not appear to trigger this issue automatically.\n\n### Root Cause\n\n- The provider detection phase mistakes \"command existence\" for \"command trustworthiness.\"\n- The `dist#vim#IsSafeExecutable()` security model already exists in the same repository, but is not reused here, leading to inconsistent protection.\n\n### Remediation Suggestions\n\n- Introduce `dist#vim#IsSafeExecutable()` or an equivalent validation before executing `npm`/`yarn`/`pnpm`/`bun`.\n- Prefer using `exepath()` to obtain absolute paths, and reject executable files from the current directory or untrusted directories.\n- Change provider detection to use list-style arguments for job invocation, reducing shell semantics injection.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.2\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 22.04\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWSL2 + Windows Terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
